lines.value: legend has it that the island of marinduque was formed as a consequence of a tragic love affair between two people marina and garduke
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: marina's father a local chieftain did not approve of this affair and ordered the beheading of garduke
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: before this could be done the couple sailed out to sea and drowned themselves forming the island now called marinduque
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: other versions of the legend also claim that the island was named malindik named after marinduque's highest mountain mt malindig
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: when spanish conquistadors arrived in the philippines they found the name hard to pronounce which led to the renaming of the island as marinduc and later the current marinduque
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: during the spanish and early american occupations marinduque was part of the province of balayan now batangas in the 16th century mindoro in the 17th century and had a brief period as an independent province in 1901 when the americans arrived
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: during the philippine american war marinduque was the first island to have american concentration camps
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: marinduque is the site of the battle of pulang lupa where filipino soldiers under colonel maximo abad defeated a larger better trained force of americans
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: in 1902 the us philippine commission annexed the islands of mindoro now two separate provinces and lubang now part of occidental mindoro to the province
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: four months later the province became part of the province of tayabas now quezon
lines.name: Waray

lines.value: on february 21 1920 act 2280 was passed by the philippine congress reestablishing marinduque as a separate province
